During a press briefing, White House Press Secretary, Karine Jean-Pierre, discussed the end of the COVID-19 public health emergency and the administration's efforts to prepare for the next phase of the response to the pandemic. She highlighted the administration's achievements in launching the largest adult vaccination program in U.S. history, sharing vaccines with other countries, and reducing COVID-19 deaths and hospitalizations. She emphasized that access to vaccines, tests, and treatments will remain widely available after the public health emergency ends. Jean-Pierre also addressed the issue of inflation, highlighting the recent decline in producer and consumer inflation rates. She mentioned the administration's efforts to lower costs for families and improve the job market. Secretary of Homeland Security, Alejandro Mayorkas, also spoke during the briefing, providing an update on border security and immigration policies. He announced the end of the Title 42 public health order and explained the transition to Title 8 processing, which will involve stricter consequences for unlawful entry at the southern border. Mayorkas acknowledged the challenges and strain on personnel and facilities, but expressed confidence in the administration's ability to manage the situation. He emphasized the importance of addressing the root causes of migration and working with regional partners to implement stronger border enforcement measures.